vector[n] mu;
for (i in 1:n) mu[i] = alpha + X[i, ] * beta;

Half-Cauchy distribution in Stan
In Stan, the half-Cauchy distribution can be specified by putting a constraint on the parameter definition.

parameters {
  real&lt;lower = 0&gt; lambda;
}
model {
  lambda ~ cauchy(0, 1);
}

Horseshoe in Stan

data {
  int&lt;lower = 1&gt; n;
  int&lt;lower = 1&gt; p;
  vector[n] Y;
  matrix[n, p] X;
  real&lt;lower = 0&gt; tau0;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;     
  real&lt;lower = 0&gt; sigma;
  vector[p] z;
  vector&lt;lower = 0&gt;[p] lambda;
  real&lt;lower = 0&gt; tau;
}
transformed parameters {
  vector[p] beta;
  beta = tau * lambda .* z;
}
model {
  // likelihood
  target += normal_lpdf(Y | alpha + X * beta, sigma);
  // population parameters
  target += normal_lpdf(alpha | 0, 3);
  sigma ~ normal(0, 3);
  // horseshoe prior
  target += std_normal_lpdf(z);
  lambda ~ cauchy(0, 1);
  tau ~ cauchy(0, tau0);
}

Modeling the scale with covariates

data {
  int&lt;lower = 1&gt; n;
  int&lt;lower = 1&gt; p;
  int&lt;lower = 1&gt; q;
  vector[n] Y;
  matrix[n, p] X;
  matrix[n, q] Z;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;
  vector[p] beta;
  vector[q] gamma;
}
transformed parameters {
  vector[n] tau = exp(Z * gamma);
}
model {
  target += normal_lpdf(Y | alpha + X * beta, tau);
}

